Differential Binding Analysis of ChIP-seq data

Introduction

The ChIP-seq data used in this workflow was generated as part of a study that investigated the regulatory role of short-chain fatty acids (SCFAs) propionate and butyrate in the context of colorectal cancer (CRC). Briefly, epigenomic and transcriptomic profiles were compared in SCFA-treated and untreated CRC cells, normal cells and in mouse intestines, with the goal of gaining insight into changes in accessibility and expression of CRC-relevant genes.

The data set used in this workflow comes from propionyl lysine (Kpr) ChIP-seq on H3K18pr and H4K12pr histone marks in CRC cells. The corresponding acetyl marks are used as controls. The data identifies genomic regions marked by Kpr following treatment with sodium propionate.

Once diffbind.sh has been run and the resulting .RData object and report.csv file are ready to be loaded into R, BiocManager, DiffBind, EnsDb.Hsapiens.v86, AnnotationDbi2, org.Hs.eg.db, ChIPpeakAnno, GenomicRanges, packages will first have to be installed.

Once the .RData object has been loaded and the dependencies installed, DiffBind will be used for exploratory analysis and for identifying differentially bound genomic coordinates. GenomicRanges will then be used to convert genomic coordinates to an annotated object. ChIPpeakAnno will be used for annotation of differentially bound regions, and ChIPseeker will provide average profile and heatmap of peak binding to TSS regions and genomic feature distribution. Finally, ReactomePA will be used to perform pathway analysis.

Goals

This workflow will perform the following analyses:

  • Compare correlations between replicates and conditions
  • Compare differential binding between histone marks
  • Display fold change of normalized read counts
  • Identify differentially bound regions
  • Create TSS distribution profiles
  • Annotate peaks and show feature distribution profiles
  • Perform pathway analysis

Setup

This R Markdown (.Rmd) file will provide a walk-through of exploratory data analysis followed by differential binding analysis, annotation and pathway analysis of histone ChIP-seq data. Each Rmd file has an initial setup chunk that applies some settings to all of the code chunks.

As in a regular R script in RStudio, a single line of code can be run with Command-Enter (Mac OS) or Ctrl-Enter (Windows). Whole chunks of code can be run with Command(/Ctrl) + Shift + Enter or by clicking the green > button in the top-right corner of the chunk. Alternatively, these options can also be implemented by selecting lines of code and choosing the desired option from the drop-down menu in the Run tab, in the top-right corner of the of Source section of RStudio.

To comment or uncomment a series of lines, highlight the lines and use Command(/Ctrl) + Shift + C.

The following Bioconductor R packages are required for this workflow. They can be installed using the following commands:

if (!requireNamespace("BiocManager", quietly = TRUE))

Exploratory and Differential Binding Analysis

Before annotation and pathway analysis it good to first visualize the data and perform quality control checks. This can be done by loading the .RData object generated by Diffbind using diffbind_chip.R script provided in the repository.

load("~/Desktop/Data/ChIP-seq/H4K12pr_ChIP.RData")

The ChIP.RData file should contain the diff object, which includes differential binding and contrast/covariate information. Make sure they are loaded into your global environment.

Check data frame information:

# This will display experimental variables defined in the sampleSheet and differentially bound sites identified by DESeq2.
diff
## 4 Samples, 91356 sites in matrix:
##      ID     Factor Condition Treatment Replicate Caller Intervals FRiP
## 1  cnt1    control   H4K12ac     10 mM         1 counts     91356 0.06
## 2  cnt2    control   H4K12ac     10 mM         2 counts     91356 0.05
## 3 prop1 propionate   H4K12pr     10 mM         1 counts     91356 0.15
## 4 prop2 propionate   H4K12pr     10 mM         2 counts     91356 0.14
## 
## 1 Contrast:
##    Group1 Members1     Group2 Members2 DB.DESeq2
## 1 control        2 propionate        2     28465

Next, its good to visualize the correlation between different replicates within each condition.

# "dba" is function that is built into DiffBind package and can be used to make plots from the "diff" object.
# "Contrast" refers to the differential analysis by factor (or condition). 
# In this example, the contrast is between prop (Kpr) vs cnt (Kac) histone marks defined in the sampleSheet.
# Replicates from the same condition should have a higher correlation score than those from different conditions.

dba.plotHeatmap(diff, contrast=1)

# Alternatively, you could also run:
#plot(diff, contrast=1)
# Generate a binding affinity heatmap showing affinities for differentially bound sites.
dba.plotHeatmap(diff, contrast=1, correlations=FALSE)

# Make an MA plot showing differentially bound sites associated with the two histone marks.
dba.plotMA(diff, bFlip=TRUE)

# Sites preferentially associated with Kpr above a significance threshold are shown as red dots in the upper panel. 
# Make a volcano plot showing the log2 fold change vs -log10 FDR-adjusted (<0.05) p-value.
dba.plotVolcano(diff, bFlip=TRUE)

Annotate to within +/- 1000 bp of transcription start sites (TSS) of a transcript.

prop.anno <- annotatePeakInBatch(propgr, AnnotationData=annoData, output="both", maxgap=1000L, select="all")

Annotate by feature.

prop.anno$gene_name <- annoData$gene_name[match(prop.anno$feature, names(annoData))]

NOTE: The final output contains a table with features showing positive and negative fold change. In this example, the positive vs negative fold change relationship is reversed, with Kpr associated genes labeled as negative fold change. You may wish to select only Kpr bound regions by opening the .report.csv or .anno.bed files in MS Excel, selecting the fold column, clicking on Sort & Filter and selecting only Greater Than or Less Than 0 entries.

Profile of Differential Binding to TSS Regions

The next several modules will require ChIPseeker and TxDb.Hsapiens.UCSC.hg38.knownGene packages.

library(ChIPseeker)

library(TxDb.Hsapiens.UCSC.hg38.knownGene)

Create a TxDb object based on the UCSC hg38 assembly of the human genome.

txdb <- TxDb.Hsapiens.UCSC.hg38.knownGene

Annotate peaks to 3000 bp upstream and downstream of promoters and generate heatmap.

promoter <- getPromoters(TxDb=txdb, upstream=3000, downstream=3000)
tagMatrix <- getTagMatrix(propgr, windows=promoter)
tagHeatmap(tagMatrix, xlim=c(-3000, 3000), color="red")

Plot peak distributions profile 3000 bp upstream and downstream of TSS.

plotAvgProf(tagMatrix, xlim=c(-3000, 3000), xlab="Genomic Region (5'->3')", ylab = "Read Count Frequency")

Resample peak distribution profile 1000 times by running bootstrapping with 0.95 confidence cutoff.

plotAvgProf(tagMatrix, xlim=c(-3000, 3000), conf = 0.95, resample = 1000)
## >> Running bootstrapping for tag matrix...        2024-03-03 21:59:59

Annotate again to 3000 bp upstream and downstream of TSS by using org.Hs.eg.db.

peakAnno <- annotatePeak(propgr, tssRegion=c(-3000, 3000), TxDb=txdb, annoDb="org.Hs.eg.db")

Pathway Analysis of Differentially Bound Genes

NOTE: As mentioned earlier, in this example, the positive vs negative fold change relationship is reversed, with Kpr associated genes assigned negative fold change. Pathways that go up or show enrichment are defined as fold < 0 and vise versa.
